ruct of capital theory or capital structures. There is some lip service paid to it, but for the most part, it's an area of study that is largely glossed over. The Austrians, thanks in large part to Mises and Hayek, have a lot of depth in this area, and I believe that's the reason why they understand the business cycle and Keynesians do not, to give an example of the broader implications of this lack of a robust theory of capital.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"95rq8\",\"text\":\"I say this because part of any robust theory of capital is an understanding of the role that time plays in investments and time to market.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"f4dtm\",\"text\":\"Essentially, changes in the protocol require changes in all of the associated infrastructure. Software needs to be updated, and this changes the hardware requirements for running the system at scale, and on the edges of profitability. These changes take time to make, and work, too for that matter. There is a cost to it.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"4dp4s\",\"text\":\"Additionally, and perhaps more importantly, it requires coordination to agree on and make these changes. But, this means that players are forced to come together and agree on all changes, despite having necessarily unequal cost/benefit effects on their firms by virtue of holding different positions of competitive advantage.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"9b4mr\",\"text\":\"So, how can those changes be done? By consolidating the competitive advantage positions, of course. It is necessarily done through a reduction in competitive advantage opportunities.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"4u8el\",\"text\":\"It should be noted that this situation isn't he case when, say, there's a terrible bug that needs to be fixed. In that case, all firms have alignment in making the change because it is a change that benefits all parties. Though the specific method of fixing the problem may be a different issue. Then it's a matter of compromise - how bad is the bug? How badly does the fix harm my firm, or benefit another firm? Etc.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"3jv30\",\"text\":\"Anyways, this is a long way of saying, it comes down to game theory, and grounding in solid, robust economic theory.\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}},{\"key\":\"9pp5e\",\"text\":\"I hope this answers your question!\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}}]}","editor2State":"{\"entityMap\":{},\"blocks\":[{\"key\":\"dcjda\",\"text\":\"\",\"type\":\"unstyled\",\"depth\":0,\"inlineStyleRanges\":[],\"entityRanges\":[],\"data\":{}}]}","postCostMilliCents":0,"purchasePriceMilliCents":null,"commentPriceMilliCents":1000,"createdAt":"2019-02-20T05:10:07.885Z","updatedAt":"2019-02-20T05:10:07.885Z","publishedAt":"2019-02-20T05:10:07.887Z","amountVotedSatoshis":0,"amountVoted":0,"nComments":0,"community":null,"totalPurchased":0,"totalTipped":10000,"totalCommented":0,"totalVoted":[{"name":"Matthew Zietzke","spent":0,"earned":0}],"url":null,"thumbnailUrl":null,"worthPayingFor":[],"notWorthPayingFor":[],"deleted":false,"isDraft":false,"editor1StateDraft":null,"editor2StateDraft":null,"titleDraft":null,"purchasePriceMilliCentsDraft":null,"commentPriceMilliCentsDraft":null,"communityDraft":null,"payments":[{"id":135797,"contentId":"2a36ce2e0f25","fromUserId":"27f4f9ef156843cd3e90649bd3b82a75da233344e7abf36b82187699dd5f148f","fromUserName":"hodler","type":"tip","toUserId":"15ca7fd9fd5e8ebbd6562475283a2ba6791d6b20afb0